# Leadership Update: Luna AI/ML Platform

Date: 17 March 2026  
Audience: Leadership and Platform Stakeholders

## Executive Summary

Luna has significantly improved the AI/ML platform foundation by replacing a fragmented legacy setup with a structured tiered model. The next critical milestone is enabling a scalable, low-friction Kubernetes-based UI hosting capability so teams can move from model development to production applications faster.

## What Has Been Achieved

1. Stabilized and rebuilt the AI platform approach after previous ownership and strategy gaps.
2. Defined a clear tiered operating model for users:
3. Basic tier for fast experimentation (quick-start resources).
4. Intermediate tier with opinionated engineering path (templates, CI/CD, Docker, Terraform, SDK/CLI).
5. Advanced tier for highly experienced teams requiring customization.
6. Improved platform usability for data scientists and ML engineers by reducing setup complexity in the core journey.

## Current Strategic Focus

1. Close the gap in UI/app hosting for AI workloads.
2. Rework and operationalize the Arkham Kubernetes path to be practical, supportable, and adoption-friendly.
3. Provide a template-led onboarding model that minimizes Kubernetes expertise required by end users.
4. Prepare for broader integration patterns, including potential Gemini/gen-AI enablement in the tiered offer.

## Why This Matters

1. Current friction slows the path from experimentation to production delivery.
2. Inconsistent app-hosting patterns increase operational risk and support burden.
3. A standardized approach will improve delivery speed, governance, and reuse across teams.

## Next-Quarter Delivery Plan

1. Deliver a working end-to-end Kubernetes onboarding and deployment pattern for 1-2 pilot teams.
2. Publish reusable templates and onboarding guidance for AI UI workloads.
3. Validate one reference deployment and operational support model.
4. Reprioritize feature-parity backlog items (for example drift detection) based on real demand and delivery impact.
5. Align stakeholders on where Gemini/gen-AI integration should sit within Luna tiers.

## Key Risks And Constraints

1. Architectural debt and over-opinionated legacy decisions in existing Kubernetes pattern.
2. Cross-team/platform governance constraints and unclear ownership boundaries.
3. Repo/environment separation model may continue to slow promotion and automation.
4. Potential scope expansion from parity asks and gen-AI ambitions without sequencing discipline.

## Decisions Needed From Leadership

1. Confirm next-quarter priority: Kubernetes UI hosting enablement as a top delivery objective.
2. Endorse a pragmatic modernization path, including revisiting legacy architecture choices where necessary.
3. Approve pilot-first rollout model (start with limited teams, then scale).
4. Agree sequencing between feature parity requests and new strategic capability work.

## Success Measures

1. Time to first deploy for pilot teams is materially reduced.
2. At least one production-credible reference deployment is delivered.
3. User onboarding is template-driven and repeatable.
4. Adoption expands beyond pilot teams with reduced platform friction and fewer escalations.

## Leadership Ask

1. Back the prioritized next-quarter scope and protect focus.
2. Support cross-team alignment to remove platform/process blockers early.
3. Sponsor adoption goals tied to measurable delivery outcomes, not only architecture completion.
